# Project 1: My Little malloc()

## Authors
Neil Barot (nnb35)
Hriday Adani (hva6)

## Design Overview
Our implementation uses a single global heap array of 4096 bytes with an implicit free list structure. Each chunk contains an 8-byte header storing size and allocation status, followed by the payload. The header size field uses the least significant bit as a flag to track whether the chunk is allocated or free.

Memory allocation uses a first-fit strategy, scanning from the beginning of the heap to find a free chunk large enough for the request. When a suitable chunk is found, it is split if there is enough remaining space for another chunk. All allocations are rounded up to multiples of 8 bytes to maintain alignment.

Free chunks are automatically coalesced with adjacent free chunks to reduce fragmentation. When freeing memory, we check both the previous and next chunks and merge them if they are free.

## Test Plan
Our testing strategy verifies both correctness and error detection:

1. Memory allocation correctness - Verify that malloc returns non-overlapping regions
2. Memory preservation - Ensure data written to allocated memory persists
3. Memory deallocation - Confirm that freed memory can be reallocated
4. Coalescing - Test that adjacent free blocks merge properly
5. Error detection - Verify all three required error cases are caught
6. Leak detection - Confirm leaked memory is reported at program exit

## Test Programs

memtest: Tests basic correctness by allocating 64 objects, writing distinct byte patterns to each, and verifying no corruption occurred. Takes no arguments. Returns 0 on success.

memgrind: Runs 5 different workload tasks 50 times each and reports average execution time. Tasks include immediate malloc/free pairs, bulk allocation/deallocation, random allocation patterns, and fragmentation scenarios. Takes no arguments.

## Build Instructions
make          # Build all targets
make clean    # Remove compiled files

## Running Tests
./memtest     # Run correctness tests
./memgrind    # Run stress tests
